[Event "Ruy Lopez: Main Lines"]
[Result "*"]

{The Ruy Lopez (or Spanish Opening) has been a cornerstone of chess for over 500 years. White develops naturally and puts long-term pressure on Black's center.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {The Ruy Lopez. White pins the knight that defends e5.} a6 {The Morphy Defense — the most popular reply, asking the bishop to declare its intentions.} (3... Nf6 {The Berlin Defense — ultra-solid, Kramnik's weapon against Kasparov in 2000.} 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {The infamous "Berlin Wall" endgame. Dull but rock-solid for Black.}) (3... d6 {The Steinitz Defense — passive but very solid.} 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. O-O Be7) (3... f5 {The Schliemann/Jaenisch Gambit — aggressive and risky.} 4. Nc3 fxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 {Sharp play.}) 4. Ba4 {Maintaining the pin. The bishop retreats but stays active.} (4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation.} dxc6 5. O-O f6 {Black gets the bishop pair and a solid pawn center.} 6. d4 Bg4 7. dxe5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 fxe5 {A slightly better endgame for White thanks to the superior pawn structure.}) Nf6 5. O-O Be7 {The Closed Ruy Lopez — the main battlefield.} (5... Nxe4 {The Open Ruy Lopez.} 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. c3 {A rich, tactical middlegame.} Bc5 (9... Be7 {The quieter option.} 10. Nbd2 Nc5 11. Bc2 O-O) 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2 {The sharp Dilworth Attack.}) 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 {Black completes the Closed Lopez setup.} 8. c3 {Preparing d4. This is the tabiya of the Closed Ruy Lopez.} O-O 9. h3 {Preventing ...Bg4 and preparing a slow kingside build-up.} Na5 {The Chigorin Variation — rerouting the knight.} (9... Nb8 {The Breyer Variation — regrouping the knight to d7.} 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 {A deep positional struggle.}) (9... Bb7 {The Zaitsev Variation.} 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a4 {Complex strategic play.}) 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 {White has a harmonious position. The game is rich with plans for both sides.} *
